An epidemic of meningitis in central and western Africa has affected thousands of people and killed hundreds, but vaccination programs are controlling the spread, according to the United Nations Childrens Fund.

Unicef said that in Chad, 4,211 cases including 400 deaths were reported. It said more than 800,000 Chadians had been vaccinated.

Chad's southern neighbor, Cameroon, reported 300 cases and 40 deaths. Unicef also reported cases in Benin, Burkina Faso and Niger. Meningitis is an inflammation of the membranes surrounding the brain.